question: What are the reported results for semi-supervised learning with 10% labels on TU datasets across the methods in 'Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations' and 'Adversarial Graph Augmentation to Improve Graph Contrastive Learning'?
answer: In the 'Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations' paper, for 10% labels on TU datasets, GraphCL achieved: NCI1: 74.63%, PROTEINS: 74.17%, DD: 76.17%, COLLAB: 74.23%, RDT-B: 89.11%, and RDT-M5K: 52.55%. In 'Adversarial Graph Augmentation to Improve Graph Contrastive Learning', AD-GCL-FIX achieved: NCI1: 75.18%, PROTEINS: 73.96%, DD: 77.91%, COLLAB: 75.82%, RDT-B: 90.10%, and RDT-M5K: 53.49%.
reference: Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations; Adversarial Graph Augmentation to Improve Graph Contrastive Learning.

question: When comparing 'Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations' and 'AutoGCL: Automated Graph Contrastive Learning via Learnable View Generators', which paper reports higher accuracy on the NCI1 dataset for semi-supervised learning with 10% of the data?
answer: In the semi-supervised learning setting with 10% data, the 'Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations' paper reports an accuracy of 74.63% on the NCI1 dataset, while 'AutoGCL: Automated Graph Contrastive Learning via Learnable View Generators' reports an accuracy of 73.75% using the default joint strategy settings.
reference: Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations; AutoGCL: Automated Graph Contrastive Learning via Learnable View Generators.

question: How do the unsupervised learning results of GraphCL and AD-GCL compare for the RDT-B dataset in the context of graph representation learning?
answer: In the unsupervised learning setting for the RDT-B dataset, the 'Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations' reports a result of 89.53%, whereas the 'Adversarial Graph Augmentation to Improve Graph Contrastive Learning' paper shows a result of 85.52%. Hence, GraphCL outperforms AD-GCL in this instance.
reference: Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations; Adversarial Graph Augmentation to Improve Graph Contrastive Learning.

question: In transfer learning settings, how does the performance of GraphCL and AD-GCL compare on the ClinTox dataset?
answer: In transfer learning settings, on the ClinTox dataset, GraphCL achieves a ROC-AUC of 75.99%, while AD-GCL achieves a significantly higher ROC-AUC of 79.78%. Hence, AD-GCL outperforms GraphCL on this dataset.
reference: Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations; Adversarial Graph Augmentation to Improve Graph Contrastive Learning.

question: Comparing 'Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations' and 'Adversarial Graph Augmentation to Improve Graph Contrastive Learning,' which method shows a better performance on the COLLAB dataset in unsupervised learning?
answer: In unsupervised learning, 'Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations' reports a performance of 71.36% in accuracy on the COLLAB dataset, whereas 'Adversarial Graph Augmentation to Improve Graph Contrastive Learning' achieves 73.32%. Thus, AD-GCL outperforms GraphCL on the COLLAB dataset for unsupervised learning.
reference: Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations; Adversarial Graph Augmentation to Improve Graph Contrastive Learning.

question: When comparing 'Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations,' 'Adversarial Graph Augmentation to Improve Graph Contrastive Learning,' and 'AutoGCL: Automated Graph Contrastive Learning via Learnable View Generators,' which method achieves the highest accuracy on the PROTEINS dataset in the unsupervised learning setting?
answer: In the unsupervised learning setting on the PROTEINS dataset, 'AutoGCL: Automated Graph Contrastive Learning via Learnable View Generators' achieves the highest accuracy with 75.80%, followed by AD-GCL with 73.59%, and then GraphCL with 74.39%. Therefore, AutoGCL achieves the highest performance on the PROTEINS dataset in this context.
reference: Graph Contrastive Learning with Augmentations; Adversarial Graph Augmentation to Improve Graph Contrastive Learning; AutoGCL: Automated Graph Contrastive Learning via Learnable View Generators.
